Tom Mitchell’s definition of machine learning:


“A computer program learns if its performance at some task \( \textbf{T} \), as measured by some metric \( \textbf{P} \), improves with experience \( \textbf{E} \).”




Definition from (Mitchell, 1997)







Real world examples of Machine Learning applications?

Machine learning applications

— Identify objects in an image
— Translate from one human language to another
— Predict outcome (e.g. medical prognosis, stock prices)
— Categorize a complex situation (e.g. medical diagnosis)
— Make decisions (e.g. in loan application)

(Roni Rosenfeld, 2016)

Real world example:



Real world example:


Identifying unsuccessful liquid handling events in an automated lab across a range of volumes, flowrates, liquid classes, and variable environmental conditions.







Where to start?

Defining the model

Using the pressure data generated during a liquid handling event, our algorithm will label that event as successful or unsuccessful.


Defining the model

Using the pressure data generated during a liquid handling event, our algorithm will label that event as successful or unsuccessful.


This type of task is called binary classification and it comes in many flavors. We will look at the simple but very widely used logistic regression algorithm.


Defining the model

Using the pressure data generated during a liquid handling event, our algorithm will label that event as successful or unsuccessful.


This type of task is called binary classification and it comes in many flavors. We will look at the simple but very widely used logistic regression algorithm.


Logistic regression attempts to learn a hyperplane that separates the data using the sigmoid function. The sigmoid function is a continuous PDF that is equally spread across a positive and negative boundary.
Given a dataset:

\( \ D = \{\vec{x}^{(i)}, y^{(i)} \}^{N}_{i=1} \ \) where \( \ \ y^{(i)} \in \{0, 1\} \)

Goal is to learn the function:

\( f: \vec{x} \rightarrow y \ \ \) or equivalently \( \ \ p(y \ |\ \vec{x}) \)

Model:

\( p_{\theta}(y=1 \ | \ \vec{x}) \equiv \sigma(\vec{\theta}^T\vec{x}) \ \ \) and \( \ \ p_{\theta}(y=0 \ | \ \vec{x}) \equiv 1 - \sigma(\vec{\theta}^T\vec{x}) \)

Objective function:

\( J_{D}(\vec{\theta}) = -log \prod^{N}_{i=1} \ p_{\theta}(y^{(i)} \ |\ \vec{x}^{(i)})\ \ \) and \( \ \ \hat{\theta} = \text{argmin}_{\theta} \ J_{D}(\vec{\theta}) \)

Decision function:

\( \hat{y} = h_{\theta}(\vec{x}_{new}) = \text{argmax}_{\{0,1\}} p_{\theta}(y \ | \ \vec{x}_{new}) \)



Where do we get \( D \)?



Where do we get \( D \)?


We can obtain the training set \( D \) by submitting runs that perform successful and unsuccessful liquid handles. i.e. pipetting of air (unsuccessful) and pipetting of actual liquid (successful).

Generating the data

Generating the data

A good training dataset will perfectly represent the data generating distribution \( p^*(\cdot) \).

Generating the data

A good training dataset will perfectly represent the data generating distribution \( p^*(\cdot) \).


We can take this into account by approximating the joint distribution over liquid handling parameters used historically, and sampling from this distribution when creating training runs.

Results

Results

Log regression + L1 normalization, volumes < 25uL 
  class   precision    recall  f1-score   support

  empty       0.49      0.94      0.64      1296
   full       0.92      0.41      0.57      2184
Log regression + L1 normalization, volumes > 25uL 
  class   precision    recall  f1-score   support

  empty       0.90      1.00      0.95      3168
   full       0.98      0.41      0.57       600
Decision tree, volumes > 25uL 
  class   precision    recall  f1-score   support

  empty       0.96      0.99      0.98      3168
   full       0.94      0.81      0.87       600
